## Forge-Powered Project

This project uses [Forge](https://forgeai.dev) for persistent memory, proactive context, and agent coordination. Forge runs alongside your AI assistant and handles context management automatically — you don't need to explain your project from scratch each session.

### What Forge Provides Automatically

- **Session memory**: Forge remembers decisions, lessons, and patterns across sessions
- **Blast radius**: Before editing any file, Forge shows what depends on it
- **Proactive context**: Anti-patterns, test reminders, and relevant decisions surface at the right moment
- **Agent teams**: For multi-file tasks, Forge coordinates planner → generator → evaluator agents

### How to Work With Forge

**Start of session**: Forge injects relevant context automatically via hooks. You'll see decisions, lessons, and working set from prior sessions. No need to re-explain the project.

**During development**: Use Forge skills for structured workflows:
```
forge:forge          — Auto-detects task type and routes to the right workflow
forge:forge-feature  — Modify existing code (explore → plan → build → review)
forge:forge-think    — Requirements discovery and BDD specs
forge:forge-review   — Code review (standard or adversarial)
forge:forge-ship     — Final verification and PR creation
```

**Storing decisions**: When you make an architectural choice, store it:
```bash
forge-next remember --type decision --title "Why we chose X" --content "Because Y and Z"
```

**Checking context**: See what Forge knows about the project:
```bash
forge-next recall "relevant topic" --project {{PROJECT_NAME}} --limit 5
forge-next blast-radius --file path/to/file
```

